      </div>
      <div class="bg-war-surface2 border-l-2 border-war-red p-4 rounded-sm mb-4">
        <div class="font-mono text-xxs text-war-red uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">Evidence</div>
        <p class="text-sm text-war-text-dim">The StreetEasy listing (Listing ID #1279480, URL: streeteasy.com/sale/1279480) displays a two-level floor plan for "13 Harrison Street, Apartment 1." The left panel is labeled "CELLAR" and the right panel is labeled "1st FLOOR."</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-war-red/5 border border-war-red/20 rounded-sm p-4 mb-4">
        <div class="font-mono text-xxs text-war-red uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">The Fraud</div>
        <p class="text-sm text-war-text-dim">The so-called "Cellar" level shows four distinct areas labeled "SLEEPING AREA" with dimensions (10'-5" × 15'-3"; 12'-0" × 15'-3"; 23'-0" × 15'-0"; and 7'-0" × 14'-0"), plus a "DEN" (23'-0" × 18'-0"). It also shows closets (CL) servicing these rooms—a functional indicator of bedroom use. Two full bathrooms are visible in the cellar layout.</p>
      </div>
      <EvidenceExhibit
        src="harassment/slide-13-streeteasy-floorplan.webp"
        alt="StreetEasy listing #1279480 floor plan showing two levels — Cellar with 4 sleeping areas labeled with dimensions, and 1st Floor"
        label="StreetEasy #1279480 — Floor Plan"
      />
    </section>

    <!-- ===================== SLIDE 14: StreetEasy "Sleeping Area" Analysis ===================== -->
    <section id="s14" data-slide="14" class="py-10 border-b border-war-border/30">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="font-mono text-xxs text-war-text-muted">14</span>
        <h3 class="section-title">Euphemism Detection: "Sleeping Area" as Code Circumvention</h3>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-war-surface2 border-l-2 border-war-amber p-4 rounded-sm mb-4">
        <div class="font-mono text-xxs text-war-amber uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">Legal Analysis</div>
        <p class="text-sm text-war-text-dim">NYC Building Code Definition: A "bedroom" or "sleeping room" is any room used or intended for sleeping (NYC Admin. Code §28-101.4.3; NYC Housing Maintenance Code). The term "Sleeping Area" is a semantic dodge—there is no legal distinction between a "sleeping area" and a "bedroom" under NYC code. Both require legally complying windows, minimum ceiling heights, and a Certificate of Occupancy designation as habitable space.</p>
      </div>
      <EvidenceExhibit
        src="harassment/slide-14-streeteasy-sleeping-area.webp"
        alt="StreetEasy listing showing 13 Harrison Street #1 — $4,750,000, floor plan with sleeping areas in cellar, David Kornmeier agent"
